  "notes": "Adyghe (адыгабзэ, West Circassian) — Northwest Caucasian, standard orthography is Cyrillic (an Arabic-based orthography is used by parts of the diaspora and is not modelled here). INPUT CONTRACT: Cyrillic text in the standard Adyghe orthography, Unicode NFC; the palochka is expected as U+04CF ⟨ӏ⟩ (lowercase) / U+04C0 ⟨Ӏ⟩ (uppercase), not the ASCII substitutes I/l/1. The alphabet is heavily DIGRAPHIC and TRIGRAPHIC: ⟨ъ⟩ marks a back/retroflex series, ⟨ӏ⟩ an ejective/glottal one and ⟨у⟩ labialisation, so sequences such as гъу, къу, кӏу, лъ, лӏ, шъу, шӏу, дзу, чъ, цӏ, ӏу spell single phonemes and are listed as their own grapheme keys (maximal munch takes the longest key first). Three vowel letters are phonemic (⟨а⟩ /aː/, ⟨э⟩ /a/, ⟨ы⟩ /ə/); ⟨е и о у ю я ё⟩ spell vowel+glide sequences and are given their surface values from the alphabet table. Standalone ⟨ъ⟩ and ⟨ь⟩ are modifier letters only and get no independent entry.",
